data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort-related patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop` while loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block doing `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** | Prevents rethrow so loop keeps running | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check; new CTS per item |
| **Thread.Abort()** call | `Stop()` force-kill | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly inject a `ThreadAbortException`. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the catch block will never fire.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Per-item CTS linked to the parent — replaces Thread.ResetAbort
            // pattern where one item's failure shouldn't kill the loop.
            using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token);    // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Whole processor is shutting down — clean up and exit
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Only the current item was cancelled (itemCts), not the loop.
                // Equivalent to the old ResetAbort — loop continues.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();   // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after Join, the thread is stuck in uncooperative code.
        // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
        // Log a warning — the IsBackground=true flag will kill it at process exit.
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
        {
            // Log: "Worker thread did not exit within timeout"
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### Key Changes Explained

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitOne`, async I/O). A bool can't interrupt `GetNextItem()` if it's blocked. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is what `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` throws |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Linked `itemCts` + `when` filter | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter distinguishes "shutdown" from "one item cancelled" |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | `Join` actually waits for the thread instead of blindly sleeping |
| (nothing) | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed to avoid timer/callback leaks |

---

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **`GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** If it blocks on a queue or I/O without checking the token, `Cancel()` won't interrupt it and the thread hangs. Use `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)` or async I/O.

2. **Token must flow through the entire call chain.** `ProcessItem` → any inner methods → any async I/O must all forward the token. One gap and cancellation stalls.

3. **`Thread.Sleep` in the loop?** Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` — it returns immediately when cancelled. `Thread.Sleep` ignores the token.

4. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` blindly.** The `when` clause is critical — without it you can't distinguish shutdown from per-item cancellation.

5. **No force-kill exists in .NET 8.** If `GetNextItem()` calls unmodifiable blocking code, your only escape hatch is moving that work to a **child process** and using `Process.Kill()`.
